  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: The Trade for That Low-Shedding Coat" imageAlt="Toy Poodle puppy being brushed during a coat care session" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>Here's the deal the Poodle offers: almost nothing on your floor, in exchange for a real grooming routine. The curly coat traps loose hair instead of dropping it, which is exactly why it mats if ignored. Plan on brushing every other day, a proper comb-through weekly, and a salon groom every 4 to 6 weeks; most Singapore owners budget $70 to $100 per session for a toy breed.</p>
      <p>In our humidity, keep the coat clipped shorter than the show-ring look and dry your puppy properly after rainy-day walks. Tear staining shows on light-coloured Poodles; the wipes in your starter kit handle it as a daily ten-second habit rather than a problem.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Toy Poodle Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Toy Poodle puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Toy Poodle goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Toy Poodle health points worth knowing: patellar luxation, the kneecap issue common to all toy breeds, which is why we discourage sofa-diving while joints grow; progressive retinal atrophy, an inherited eye condition the breed carries, worth asking about in any Poodle line; dental crowding, because small jaws need the oral care routine from day one; and Legg-Calvé-Perthes, a hip condition seen occasionally in toy breeds.</p>
      <p>None of this changes the headline: a well-bred Toy Poodle is one of the longest-lived dogs you can own, with 14 to 17 years the normal expectation. Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. For portioning guidance see the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <div class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="The Truth About Teacup Poodles" imagePosition="none" variant="card">
      <p>After the Chihuahua, no breed gets more "teacup" marketing than the Toy Poodle. You will see "teacup poodle" and "micro poodle" listings around Singapore, usually at a premium. We don't sell to that label. Dogs bred to be unusually tiny carry higher risks: fragile bones, severe dental problems, chronic low blood sugar, and shorter lives.</p>
      <p>A healthy Toy Poodle at 3 to 4.5 kg is already a genuinely small dog that rides in a carrier and lives happily in a flat. If a seller guarantees an adult size below that range, treat the promise as a warning, not a feature.</p>
      <div slot="side" class="clay h-full bg-[var(--color-peach-100)] p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs font-bold uppercase text-[var(--color-cream-500)]" style="letter-spacing: 0.08em;">Teacup red flags</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3">
          {[
            'Guaranteed adult weight below 3 kg',
            'No mention of the parents\' actual size',
            '"Teacup" or "micro" priced at a premium',
          ].map((fact) => (
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-cream-700)]">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" class="mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-[var(--color-coral-500)]" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M18 6 6 18M6 6l12 12" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" />
              </svg>
              {fact}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </CaptionedBlock>

    <PawTrail bg="bg-[var(--color-surface)]" colorClass="text-[var(--color-coral-300)]" />
  </div>

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Toy Poodle's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Toy Poodle puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Toy Poodle explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and predictable. A fixed feeding routine, the toilet pads where we placed them, and short, gentle play. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment, and Poodle puppies settle fast once the routine reads as safe.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, and this brain starts looking for work. This is the window to book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer; see <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>. For anything in between, you WhatsApp us.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

